                      <chapter>
                        <title>Brazil vs. WhatsApp</title>
                        <paragraph>A Brazilian judge issued a 72-hour ban on Facebook Inc.’s WhatsApp throughout
                          Brazil on Monday. Messaging service was ordered blocked in Brazil for the second
                          time in less than six months for failing to turn over data in a criminal investigation.</paragraph>
                          <paragraph>WhatsApp, is ubiquitous in Brazil. The app popularity explains why the judge’s ruling
                            to block the app in Brazil.</paragraph>
                            <paragraph>Others sought free messaging apps to avoid paying for texts or phone calls.
                              Telegram Messenger, which got a boost in Brazil in December, said on
                              Twitter that almost a million new users have joined.</paragraph>
                              <paragraph>
                                <list type="ordered">
                                  <item>May 2nd, 2016: Judge Marcel Montalvao, from the northeastern state
                                    of Sergipe, told phone companies to block WhatsApp</item>
                                    <item>December 17th, 2015: Judge Sandra Regina Nostre Marques ordered the service
                                      to be blocked from Brazil’s end</item>
                                    </list>
                                  </paragraph>
                                  <paragraph>On December 17th 2015, Mark Zuckerberg shared this post on Facebook: "Tonight,
                                    a Brazilian judge blocked WhatsApp for more than 100 million people who rely
                                    on it in her country. We are working hard to get this block reserved. Until then,
                                    Facebook Messenger is still active and you can use it to communicate instead.
                                    This is a sad day for Brazil. Until today, Brazil has been an ally in creating an
                                    open internet. Brazilians have always been among the most passionate in sharing their voice online."</paragraph>
                                    <paragraph>On May 2nd 2016, Telegram Messenger share this post on Twitter: "Sorry Brazil! Your mobile networks
                                      can't process as many verification SMS as we're sending them. Over a million
                                      users joined, more waiting."</paragraph>
                                    </chapter>
